Almost any iambic succession of syllables with an accent next .to the long syllable may be treated as two short syllables, but the frequency with which the shortened form of each word occurs reflects roughly the usage of ordinary speech.²

ln Plautus and Terence there occur a number of shortened iambi which do not seem to have aword or sentence accent on the syllable preceding or following the shortened syllable, and in some of these the shortened syllable itself seems to be accented. lt is possible that in some cases our information as to early Latin accent is defective, but most such irregulari- ties are probably due to the influence of related words which fulfilled the conditions of the change; tibique is due, then, to tibi, ne'scid (340, etc.) to scih, ddvenls (909) to alnis, eddem (885) to Ε’ὄ, edrum (64, etc.) to idru'mque and ἔὸνάπᾶιηι, fuisse (42) to such forms as fril, salisse'mun and fdlstique, · ddccinist (236, etc.) to liic ist, etc.
